03959nam a22005775i 9780674266117DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222001mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742661177 a10.4159/97806742661172doi  a(DE-B1597)589292  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aPHI0190002bisacsh1 aMiller, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrinciples of Social Justice /cDavid Miller. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 The Scope of Social Justice -- t2 A Sketch of a Theory of Justice -- t3 Social Science and Political Philosophy -- t4 Distributive Justice: What the People Think -- t5 Procedures and Outcomes -- t6 Virtues, Practices, and Justice -- t7 The Concept of Desert -- t8 Deserving Jobs -- t9 Two Cheers for Meritocracy -- t10 “To Each According to His Needs” -- t11 Equality and Justice -- t12 Prospects for Social Justice -- tNotes -- tCredits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSocial justice has been the animating ideal of democratic governments throughout the twentieth century. Even those who oppose it recognize its potency. Yet the meaning of social justice remains obscure, and existing theories put forward by political philosophers to explain it have failed to capture the way people in general think about issues of social justice. This book develops a new theory. David Miller argues that principles of justice must be understood contextually, with each principle finding its natural home in a different form of human association. Because modern societies are complex, the theory of justice must be complex, too. The three primary components in Miller's scheme are the principles of desert, need, and equality. The book uses empirical research to demonstrate the central role played by these principles in popular conceptions of justice. It then offers a close analysis of each concept, defending principles of desert and need against a range of critical attacks, and exploring instances when justice requires equal distribution and when it does not. Finally, it argues that social justice understood in this way remains a viable political ideal even in a world characterized by economic globalization and political multiculturalism. Accessibly written, and drawing upon the resources of both political philosophy and the social sciences, this book will appeal to readers with interest in public policy as well as to students of politics, philosophy, and sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674266117zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674266117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674266117/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK